Tasks.json

DATA STORAGE AND RETRIEVAL

This is Data Storage
Task is created and stored in a memory mat
this.tasks[task.id] = task; //javescript 
so the data us kept like
"abc123": Task

you then then need to convert the data into an array for storage
const tasksArray = Object.values(this.tasks);
this means it occur on json as 
{task1},
{task2}

it is the written to disk
fs.writeFileSync(this.storagePath, JSON.stringify(tasksArray, null, 2));

For Data Retrieval
when the app starts it is loaded
this.load()

It will then look if the file exists
fs.existsSync(this.storagePath)

it will read a file
const rawData = fs.readFileSync(this.storagePath, 'utf8');

After reading the file. it will parse it to json
const tasksData = JSON.parse(rawData);

It will then rebuild the Task object for each object and proceeds to restore fields manually
task.id = taskData.id;
task.priority = taskData.priority;
task.status = taskData.status;
task.createdAt = new Date(taskData.createdAt);
task.updatedAt = new Date(taskData.updatedAt);

it will then store everything in the memory map
this.tasks[task.id] = task;


I found the Repository Pattern interesting.
instead of directly interacting with the file system everywhere. all data goes through one class

my initial understanding priority is a label shown to users and helps sjow which tasks are important. in my understanding it gets passed through the system without much logic. 
However, I discovered it is a core system attribute. It is a fundamental property of a task.  I discovered that priority us used in actual logic in filering tasks by priority and organising task list

Priority is part of the tasks identity and not just a presentation. it is also a pass through value across the system.  The task priority is a system that influences filtering and organisation.

